### Generics in Rust

Generics allow writing code that works with multiple types while maintaining type safety. They are a form of parametric polymorphism.

---

### Generic Syntax

| Context | Syntax |
|---------|--------|
| Functions | `fn name<T>(arg: T) -> T` |
| Structs | `struct Point<T> { x: T, y: T }` |
| Enums | `enum Option<T> { Some(T), None }` |
| Methods | `impl<T> Point<T> { fn x(&self) -> &T }` |

---

### Examples

```rust
// Generic function
fn largest<T: PartialOrd>(list: &[T]) -> &T {
    let mut largest = &list[0];
    for item in list {
        if item > largest {
            largest = item;
        }
    }
    largest
}

// Generic struct
struct Pair<T, U> {
    first: T,
    second: U,
}

// Generic impl
impl<T, U> Pair<T, U> {
    fn new(first: T, second: U) -> Self {
        Self { first, second }
    }
}

// Monomorphization: compiler generates concrete code for each type
let result = largest(&vec![1, 2, 3]);      // i32 version
let result = largest(&vec!['a', 'b', 'c']); // char version
```

> **Key Point:** Generics in Rust are monomorphized at compile time, meaning there is no runtime overhead. The compiler generates separate code for each concrete type used. This is zero-cost abstraction.

codeExample:
struct Point<T> {
    x: T,
    y: T,
}

impl<T> Point<T> {
    fn x(&self) -> &T {
        &self.x
    }
}

impl Point<f64> {
    fn distance_from_origin(&self) -> f64 {
        (self.x.powi(2) + self.y.powi(2)).sqrt()
    }
}

fn main() {
    let p = Point { x: 5, y: 10 };
    println!("p.x = {}", p.x());

    let pf = Point { x: 3.0, y: 4.0 };
    println!("Distance: {}", pf.distance_from_origin());
}
